05577nam a22006135i 9780822390749DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20102009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223907497 a10.1515/97808223907492doi  a(DE-B1597)554447  a(OCoLC)631195264  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aCB425 7aART0090002bisacsh00aRuins of Modernity /cJulia Hell, Andreas Schönle, George Steinmetz, Julia Adams. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (528 p.) :b83 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics, History, and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tAUTHENTIC RUINS -- tAIR WAR AND ARCHITECTURE -- tMODERNISM AND DESTRUCTION IN ARCHITECTURE -- tRUINS OF THE AVANT-GARDE -- tMODERNITY AS A ''DESTROYED ANTHILL'' -- tDEMOCRATIC DESTRUCTION -- tTHE RUINS OF A REPUBLIC -- tLAYERED TIME -- tCITIES, CITIZENSHIP, AND OTHER JOBURG STORIES -- tIMPERIAL RUIN GAZERS, OR WHY DID SCIPIO WEEP? -- tHEGEL'S PHILOSOPHY OF WORLD HISTORY VIA SEBALD'S IMAGINARY OF RUINS -- tVILCASHUAMÁN -- tTHE MONUMENT IN RUINS -- tSIMULTANEOUS MODERNITY -- tRUINS AS MODELS -- t''MEMORY TRACES OF AN ABANDONED SET OF FUTURES'' -- tCOLONIAL MELANCHOLY AND FORDIST NOSTALGIA -- tDR. STRANGELOVE'S CABINET OF WONDER -- tINVISIBLE AT A GLANCE -- tFOUNDATIONAL RUINS -- tTHE PROMISE OF A RUIN -- tRUIN CINEMA -- tTHE PLACE OF RUBBLE IN THE TRÜMMERFILM -- tLOST IN TIME -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aImages of ruins may represent the raw realities created by bombs, natural disasters, or factory closings, but the way we see and understand ruins is not raw or unmediated. Rather, looking at ruins, writing about them, and representing them are acts framed by a long tradition. This unique interdisciplinary collection traces discourses about and representations of ruins from a richly contextualized perspective. In the introduction, Julia Hell and Andreas Schönle discuss how European modernity emerged partly through a confrontation with the ruins of the premodern past.Several contributors discuss ideas about ruins developed by philosophers such as Immanuel Kant, Georg Simmel, and Walter Benjamin. One contributor examines how W. G. Sebald's novel The Rings of Saturn betrays the ruins erased or forgotten in the Hegelian philosophy of history. Another analyzes the repressed specter of being bombed out of existence that underpins post-Second World War modernist architecture, especially Le Corbusier's plans for Paris. Still another compares the ways that formerly dominant white populations relate to urban-industrial ruins in Detroit and to colonial ruins in Namibia. Other topics include atomic ruins at a Nevada test site, the connection between the cinema and ruins, the various narratives that have accrued around the Inca ruin of Vilcashuamán, Tolstoy's response in War and Peace to the destruction of Moscow in the fire of 1812, the Nazis' obsession with imperial ruins, and the emergence in Mumbai of a new "kinetic city" on what some might consider the ruins of a modernist city. By focusing on the concept of ruin, this collection sheds new light on modernity and its vast ramifications and complexities.Contributors. Kerstin Barndt, Jon Beasley-Murray, Russell A. Berman, Jonathan Bolton, Svetlana Boym, Amir Eshel, Julia Hell, Daniel Herwitz, Andreas Huyssen, Rahul Mehrotra, Johannes von Moltke, Vladimir Paperny, Helen Petrovsky, Todd Presner, Helmut Puff, Alexander Regier, Eric Rentschler, Lucia Saks, Andreas Schönle, Tatiana Smoliarova, George Steinmetz, Jonathan Veitch, Gustavo Verdesio, Anthony Vidler  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's W